        <td bgcolor="dimgray" colspan="2" valign="top">
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="1">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;03/26/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 00:27:05</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=3880"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
 
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=3880')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=TopicQuote&TOPIC_ID=2015&FORUM_ID=2&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=General+Discussions&Topic_Title=Inter%2DCaster+Balance"><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"> Because I am largely ignorant of <i>Necromancer</i> issues much beyond what little I have read here, and some experience grouping with <i>Necromancers</i>, I am cross posting this in an effort to elicit your opinions on how the various caster classes should stand with respect to one another.</P><P>Inter-Caster Balance</P><P><i>Verant</i> has stated that they are in the midst of <i>Caster versus Melee Balance</i>, and additionally have indicated some openess towards <i>Magician Class Balance</i> as well <i>(assuming Summoned Focus Items are not it)</i>.  And as <i>Magicians</i> we have more than a passing interest in this subject.</P><P>However, balance of a specific class cannot be discussed entirely or perhaps even fruitfully in isolation from other classes.  This includes the other classes that we group or raid with, who support us or whom we support, but also the classes we are most obviously compared with, that is <u>Intelligence Casters</u>: <i>Wizard, Magician, Necromancer</i> and <i>Enchanter</i>.</P><P>I will state in advance that I understand <i>Magicians</i> the best, of course, <i>Wizards</i> only though the obvious comparisons with ourselves and my reading on Graffes, and <i>Necromancers</i> and <i>Enchanters</i> far less.  But then, that is the point of discussion, the exchange of ideas and information.</P><P>I beleive that <i>Wizards</i> will be adjusted first, as they are in a sense the archetype or purest form of intelligence caster.  They deal primarily with various forms of direct damage, which is comparatively straightforward to analyze.  <i>Focus Effects</i> have had the greatest impact on <i>Wizards</i>.  Direct damage spells appear to be the caster equivalent of combat, the simplest way to deal damage for casters.  It seems that <i>Wizards</i> might be fixed primarily by adjusting their damage output sufficiently to distinguish them from other casters.</P><P>Then, once <i>Wizards</i> are set, other casters can be adjusted appropriately.  It does seem to me that fixing pets is a much more complex problem than adjusting direct damage output.</P><P>The most obvious way that caster classes differ from one another is in their direct damage output.  In order from greatest to least, the classes would probably rank: <i>Wizard, Magician, Necromancer, Enchanter</i>.  I am not sure really how to account for <i>Necromancer</i> dots, except to point out that they currently do not stack, whereas direct damage does, which is why I ranked <i>Necromancers</i> below <i>Magicians</i></P><P>Another way that caster classes differ from one another is in their impact against magic resistant enemies.  In this case, I would rank the casters in this order: <i>Enchanter, Magician, Necromancer, Wizard</i>.  My reasoning here is that <i>Enchanters</i> can enhance melee damage output <u>and</u> can charm a mob with significant melee output, <i>Magicians</i> have summonable pets which melee and are stronger than <i>Necromancer</i> summoned pets, while <i>Wizards</i> are largely out of luck if the mobs resist their spells.</P><P>Crowd control is another dimension, and here I would rank classes: <i>Enchanter, Necromancer, Wizard, Magician</i>.  I rank <i>Magician</i> below <i>Wizard</i> as an elemental can only deal with at most one foe, and <i>Wizards</i> have <i>Root</i> available to them, which is commonly refered to as <i>"Ghetto Mezz."</i></P><P>Long term sustained damage output is an important measure.  This I am much less sure of, as I do not understand <i>Necromancers</i> much.  Based on what I have seen posted by others, the rankings might be: <i>Necromancer, Magician, Wizard, Enchanter</i>.  I rank <i>Magician</i> above <i>Wizard</i> because of elementals, which require little mana to maintain and which output damage even while medding.  I rank <i>Necromancer</i> above that because they appear to be able to regenerate mana without depending on another class, and have damage over time spells that are said to be quite impressive.  I am less sure about this ranking, however, as it based on guesses.</P><P>I am not sure what, if anything, to conclude from these rankings, but only present them to start discussion.</P><P>My gut feelings are that <i>Wizard</i> nukes need to distinguished more from other classes, <i>Magician</i> pets need to improved against higher end mobs, <i>Necromancer</i> dots need either to be stackable or they should have some other way of dealing damage that does not conflict, and I am not sure at all what class balance issues <i>Enchanters</i> face, except perhaps a lack of stackability on raids.</P><P><b>Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><BR>Senior ArchMage, Ancient Fellowship, Xev</P><P><BR>Razamatazz Pizzazz<BR>Mage of a Thousand Words</font></td>

      </tr>

