        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"> Thank you for your thoughtful responses, dread cousins.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>1. Enchanters stick out, they are no damage dealer, they are for crowd control/slow/haste/crack, they are wanted in groups and they are balanced. PERIOD<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>This is my opinion also, but I feel under-informed regarding <i>Enchanters</i> and would like their perspective as well.<BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Maybe their pets should have good ac/resistance/hp so that their pet can tank even the very hard mobs for a while. So this could help with a pull that went wrong.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>A great deal of <i>Magicians</i> feel that the major class balance issue for them is viable pets post-55, and especially post-60.<BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Master of long fights, master of damage dealt over time<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>So I have heard.  My understanding is that <i>Damage over Time</i> spells are quite powerful and efficient, but as I have are a couple really crappy ones, I am not sure how they effect playing style.</P><P>One point does occur to me though.  How long is long?  I mean how do you set it up so that <i>DoTs</i> dominate long fights without having them also dominate medium length fights.?  Seems to me to accomplish this, what would work is are REALLY long but very effective DoTs.  If the length of a DoT is substantially less than the length of the fight, then barring stacking issues, it almost might as well have been a nuke.</P><P>How many seconds is a long fight?<BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>The 3 damage dealing melees (ranger, monk, rogue) should rank well above the tank classes, but behind the casting classes in short time encounters AND in long time encounters.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>This is a matter of some debate, as I understand.  The common counter argument I hear is that it would dramatically reduce the desirability of melees.  I agree that they are mostly too valuable as presently constituted.  I feel that the caster damage output and melee damage output should be roughly comparable, so that no one feels like a moron choosing one over the other.<BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>I think Verant is misguided in their attempts to "balance" casters vs. melee because of the fact that healer classes have been lumped in with pure casters. Look at the nerf of the mage summoned items with regard to Complete Heal and you'll see how this problem has surfaced.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>I agree here that there have been some negative consequences here.  So far as I can tell, the priest classes are already pretty much balanced.  They are necessary, and they do well.  Even though the focus effects have been adjusted to minimize their impact on healing, I find <i>Druids</i> regularly outnuke me, and <i>Clerics</i> rivalling me.  At the very least it is worth asking, <i>"Is this what we want?"</i><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>I've never heard of a raid cancelled by a lack of mages<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>In our guild, I often feel pressure to continue raiding, as <i>Rods of Transvergence</i> are vital to our mix of classes, especially in long fights.  They dramatically reduce prep time, down time, help compensate for under represented classes, and help sustain long fights.  I feel I perform a vital role in our guild, and we have half a dozen active post-50 mages.<BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>I think the pet classes need some serious upgrades and fixes in order for us to remain viable.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>Agreed, but this involves a complex set of issues, and I suspect will be towards the end of caster balance.</P><P><b><i>Tencor</i>:</b> Very thoughtful comments.  My main questions, and they are questions, not assertions, is how do you arrange it so that <i>DoTs</i> are best for long term fights, but do not dominate medium fights?<BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Everything is situational. Without explaining the specifics of a situation, then you cannot analyze. It may be better to pick a few specific situations and explain the usefulness of classes in those situations.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>Yes, but in order to analyze, we must first simplify.  These simplifications reveal some limited insights, and then used to build more complex analysis.  That is why DPS is the starting point for so many discussions.  The problem is when overly general conclusions are made from simple analysis.<BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>I find it rather amusing that VI dislikes soloing so much.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>I think in general, soloing should be largely ignored for discussions of class balance, except insofar as proposed changes might break soloing.  <i>Slow</i> has an enormous impact on soloing, but no one proposes removing it or substantially reducing its effect.<BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Wizards are ALREADY kings of the short fights. With their AA skills in SCF they do even more. What more do Wizards want?<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>My understanding is that especially pre-50 they do not feel balanced.  Post-60 does not appear to be a major problem for <i>Wizards</i>.<BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>If you are ignorant of necromancers then dont bother starting a post on necro/int caster balancing, it makes you look like a bullshit artist.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote>I came here asking questions in a respectful manner, and was very clear about what I did not know.  Since when is soliciting information and opinions from other with different experience and perspectives inappropriate?  Is not the purpose of this and other forums to exchange information?</P><P>If I have questions about <i>Necromancers</i>, or seek their opinions, where else should I go <u>but</u> this forum?</P><P>Thank you for these thoughtful replies.</P><P><BR>Razamatazz Pizzazz<BR>Mage of a Thousand Words<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
